sec.p:
The Argentinean Tierra del Fuego belongs to the Araucarian-Antarctic biogeographic region (Rapoport 
1968
). The first paper on 
Collembola
from this region by Schäffer (
1897
) described a new species of 
Tullbergia
(
Aphorura trisetosa
). Later authors published papers on the 
Collembola
of that region: Wahlgren (
1906
), Willem (
1902
), Enderlein (
1912
), Rapoport & Rubio (
1968
), Najt (
1973
), Rubio (
1974
), Block (
1992
), Weiner & Najt (
1996
).

In the description I use the nomenclature for morphological features as proposed by Jordana 
et al.
(
1997
) and Weiner & Najt (
1991
). Pseudocellar formulae are the number of pseudocelli by half-tergite as follows: head anterior, head posterior/ Th I, Th II, Th III/Abd I, Abd II, Abd III, Abd IV, Abd V. Pseudocellar 
type
is after Weiner & Najt (
1991
). Formula of tibiotarsal chaetotaxy is after Deharveng (
1983
) and Fjellberg (
1991
): total number of chaetae (number of chaetae in the distal whorl (A+T), number of chaetae in the proximal whorl (B)). Antennal chaetae is after Rusek (
1971
) and D’Haese (
2003
).

tp:treatment-sec.p:
Type locality. Argentina , Tierra del Fuego, near Rio Grande ( 53 º 36 ’ S
, 68 º 04’ W
).

Description. Habitus as in
. Body length (without antennae) 1.6 mm (female holotype ), 1.3–1.8 mm (female paratypes ), 1.1–1.6 mm (male paratypes ). Body white. Cuticular granulation of whole body relatively uniform, consisting of small secondary granules 1–1.5 mm in diameter, with areas of large ones, especially on head and dorsum of Abd V–VI, where they reach 2–3.5 mm in diameter. Antennal bases and posterior parts of Th II–III and Abd I–V bear bands of dense granulation formed by small granules 0.8–1.5 mm in diameter. Dorsal chaetae well differentiated into meso- and macrochaetae (
).

Antennae slightly shorter than head length (
), ratio of lengths 1 : 1.4 . Ant I, II, and III with 8, 11, and 17 ordinary chaetae respectively. AIIIO consists of three large sensory clubs with papillate protecting integumentary fold covering two small sensory rods between the two outermost of these clubs, single sensillum located ventrally on Ant III. Ant IV with five thickened and curved sensilla (S 1 , S 4 , S 7 , S 8 and S 9 after D’Haese ( 2003 ) = e, c, b, a and d respectively after Rusek ( 1971 )), one dorsoexternal microsensillum and one small subapical organite; apical vesicle trilobed (
).

PAO narrow elliptical, in shallow depression, 7–8 times longer than diameter of the nearest pso, and slightly longer than width of the Ant I, consisting of 75–95 simple vesicles lying in two parallel rows (
). Labial palp with 3 papillae A, B, D (papillae C and E absent), 6 proximal chaetae and 3 hypostomal chaetae (
). Basal parts of labium with 4 + 4 and 5 + 5 chaetae. Maxillary palp simple, without sublobal hair (
). Chaetotaxy of labrum: 4 /3,4,2.

Body length (without antennae) about 0.4 mm . PAO different to that of adult animals, with about 22 simple vesicles (
). AIIIO and sensory complex on Ant IV different to adult animals: simple and consisting only of one inner sensory club and two minute sensory rods. From sensory complex on Ant IV only the subapical organite and the dorso-external microsensillum present. Sensilla a–e and apical papilla mising, as well as most chaetae (
). Dorsal chaetotaxy strongly reduced (
and
Table 2 );psoexceptionally large and reduced in number (pso not seen on Th I and dorso-lateral position of Abd IV).

Description of Second instar .
and
represents the sensorial apparatus of Ant III–IV, dorsal chaetotaxy, arrangement of pso and morphology of PAO in second instar larvae. Body length (without antennae) about 0.8 mm . PAO similar to that of adult animals, with about 50 simple vesicles (
). AIIIO with only two sensory clubs and two minute sensory rods with papillate integumentary fold (the inner sensory club missing). Sensory complex on Ant IV the same as adult animals (
). Dorsal chaetotaxy reduced, specially the chaetae in m-row (
and
Table 3 ); pso as in adult animals; psp missing (
).

